<HEADLINE>
FT  17 NOV 92 / Contractors protest over bridge bids: Heseltine is urged to
intervene
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR, Construction Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH steelwork contractors have asked Mr Michael Heseltine, the trade and
industry secretary, to intervene after two Italian companies submitted the
lowest bids for bridge contracts worth Pounds 30m.
The steel contractors, which claim unfair competition, say the contracts
include steelwork for the Pounds 300m privately financed second Severn
bridge.
The British Constructional Steelwork Association said Cimolai, an Italian
contractor which has worked in Britain since the early 1980s, had submitted
the lowest tender for the Severn bridge.
It also said that Beghini Steel UK, a subsidiary of a Verona-based company,
had submitted the lowest bids for the steelwork for the Thelwell viaduct
across the M6 in Cheshire and for bridges across the extension of the M3
near Winchester.
The association says the three contracts could provide 3,000 jobs for UK
contractors.
Mr Allan Collins, the association's president, says in a letter to Mr
Heseltine: 'This is a very serious undermining of the policy to stimulate UK
construction activity.'
The letter asks the secretary of state to call an immediate meeting with
main contractors involved in the bridge building programme to discuss the
problem of cut-price tenders from overseas suppliers.
It adds: 'This is not a case of just bleating because we are about to lose.
'We, as an industry, are being battered to death, yet we are without doubt
the most efficient producer of fabricated steelwork in Europe.
'This begs the question of how the Italians are getting in with prices up to
20 per cent below our own suppliers'.'
Dr Derek Tordoff, the association's director, said yesterday: 'We believe
that many Italian fabricators receive hidden subsidies and that they have
been targeting Britain and other international markets in order to make up
for a decline in Italian construction activity.'
According to Dr Tordoff more than 100 UK steel contractors have ceased
trading or gone into receivership since 1989. Numbers employed have fallen
by 40,000 to 60,000.
Four of the largest publicly quoted companies in the sector - Graham Wood,
Ward Group, Conder and Henry Barratt - have seen all or part of their
businesses go into receivership since the spring.
Dr Tordoff warned that further job losses were inevitable, with the industry
still suffering from over-capacity in spite of the recent closures.
</TEXT>
