<HEADLINE>
FT  17 NOV 92 / Demand for offices in London increases
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VANESSA HOULDER, Property Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE AVAILABILITY of office space in central London has fallen significantly
for the first time in five years, Debenham Tewson Research, chartered
surveyors, said yesterday.
It attributed the change largely to increased demand for new, centrally
located offices by the financial sector. Supply and demand for office space
are closer to balance than at any time since autumn 1987, when the impact of
the construction boom had still to be felt.
The amount of office space in central London that can be occupied
immediately or within six months fell from 34.3m sq ft to 33.5m sq ft in the
third quarter. That was because of a 27 per cent rise in the take-up of
space from 2.6m sq ft to 3.3m sq ft, and a 6 per cent fall in the space
coming on to the market from 4.5m sq ft to 4.2m sq ft.
Availability in central locations fell 4 per cent to 24.3m sq ft while
take-up rose nearly 40 per cent. On the fringes of London availability rose
marginally, take-up fell by more than a fifth and the space coming on the
market almost doubled.
Although more than half the take-up was of newly built space, almost
four-fifths of the space coming on the market was second-hand.
Central London Office Report, Research &amp; Information Services, Debenham
Tewson &amp; Chinnocks, 44 Brook Street, London W1A 4AG. Pounds 25.
</TEXT>
