<HEADLINE>
FT  17 NOV 92 / High earners shun holidays in Britain
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SKAPINKER, Leisure Industries Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITONS WITH higher incomes are cutting back on holidays in the UK so that
they can continue going abroad, the English Tourist Board said yesterday.
Mr Mike Richardson, marketing director of the tourist board, said yesterday
that weekend breaks in the UK were down between 5 per cent and 10 per cent
in the first eight months of this year.
Many higher earners appeared to have rejected the idea of taking a cheaper
overseas trip so that they could continue to take holidays in the UK, he
said.
'The higher-income groups tend to take more than one holiday a year and the
greater proportion take their main holiday overseas. English holidays
account for the greater proportion of second holidays. Now that the
recession has hit, people are holding on to their overseas holiday,' he
said.
The fall in the pound would help to make holidays in the UK cheaper and
trips abroad more expensive, he added. But the board would find it difficult
to market UK holidays following the government's decision, announced last
week, to cut its grant from Pounds 15.6m this year to Pounds 9.1m in 1995.
Mr Richardson said: 'It's all very well having a competitively priced
product, but it doesn't help if you can't tell people about it. Devaluation
has created a better climate for promotion of UK holidays but it is not a
panacea.'
Other countries would be able to spend more on their marketing effort in the
UK as a result of devaluation, he explained.
</TEXT>
