<HEADLINE>
FT  17 NOV 92 / Bar backs late sittings for small-claims courts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT RICE, Legal Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE BAR called on the government yesterday to set up a limited pilot scheme
to extend the opening hours of magistrates' courts and small-claims courts
from 5.30pm until 8.30pm.
A working party set up last year to look at the need for extended court
hours said in its report that people running small businesses might not be
able to afford to take time off work to pursue claims.
The frequency of night sittings would depend on demand but at the outset
would be three times a week every second week.
Ms Anesta Weekes, head of working party, said the court system had to be run
more with the interests of the consumer in mind.
Extended hours would also encourage defendants involved in minor cases to
attend court rather than plead guilty by post, she said.
Defendants arrested late in the day could be bailed by magistrates instead
of being remanded in custody overnight. In magistrates' courts evening
sessions would be limited to certain types of case, including bail
applications; minor motoring offences; non-payment of fines; and guilty
pleas where there was no risk of a custodial penalty.
Using court buildings for longer periods would reduce delays and cut the
backlog of cases, Ms Weekes said.
The working party studied the experience of courts in New York, which have
been opening in the evenings and throughout the night for more than 20
years, and an experiment of evening sessions at Uxbridge magistrates' court,
west London, last year.
</TEXT>
