<HEADLINE>
FT  17 NOV 92 / Governments reach accord on N Ireland talks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM COONE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   DUBLIN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE BRITISH and Irish governments have agreed to try to restart political
talks in Northern Ireland in the new year.
The talks, involving both governments and the four main political parties in
the province, broke up last week without agreement and no clear commitment
to renew dialogue.
The discussions had sought an agreement on a new devolved administration in
Northern Ireland, and a replacement of the 1985 agreement.
Both governments agreed in Dublin yesterday 'that the objectives of the
talks process are both valid and achievable'.
Sir Patrick Mayhew, the Northern Ireland secretary, and Mr David Andrews,
the Irish foreign minister, agreed that the most fruitful stage of the talks
had occurred in the past four weeks, when the round-table plenary and
committee stages were abandoned in favour of bilateral meet-ings.
Sir Patrick said: 'People got on better on a party-to-party and a one-to-one
basis.'
Mr Andrews admitted that there had been no bilateral meeting between the
Irish government and the Democratic Unionist party led by the Rev Ian
Paisley. 'We would like to meet the DUP in bilateral talks,' he said. The
value of any future talks would be greatly diminished without such a
meeting.'
He criticised the a la carte approach of the DUP to the past series of
meetings, but praised the 'moderate and very conciliatory' approach of Mr
James Molyneaux, the leader of the Ulster Unionist party.
Yesterday's meeting dealt at length with the upsurge in paramilitary
violence in the North. Mr Padraig Flynn, the Irish justice minister, said
there now existed a threat of the violence extending into the Irish
Republic.
The meeting, on the seventh anniversary of the signing of the 1985
Hillsborough agreement, was the first bilateral discussion under the
agreement since April, when regular meetings were adjourned to allow the
inter-party talks to take place. The unionist parties oppose the 1985
agreement because of the role it gives to the Republic in Northern Ireland's
affairs, and refuse to participate in talks while the intergovernmental
meetings continue.
The governments have agreed to meet 'as soon as is practicable' before
Christmas with a further intergovernmental conference in the new year. That
would establish a new pause in the process so that the multilateral talks
could begin again.
</TEXT>
