<HEADLINE>
FT  17 NOV 92 / Building societies and banks become whipping boys again:
John Gapper examines the background to accusations that lenders are failing
to pass on interest rate cuts to customers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
YESTERDAY was a typical enough day for the heads of banks and building
societies under Mr John Major's government. They were given a public
scolding about their alleged failure to pass on cuts in base rates to
mortgages and small business loans. As the recession has lingered, such
tickings-off have become frequent.
The admonition was not as severe as in the past. The chancellor's statement
after his chat with building societies and the Housing Corporation, the
quango which finances housing association homes, yesterday focused mainly on
his plan to inject Pounds 750m into the housing market. But he warned them
that he wanted to see cheaper loans.
The banks and building societies offer similar defences to the charge of
profiteering. Two high-street banks say they have widened margins to reflect
the higher risk of bad loans in a recession. Building societies say wider
margins are needed to pay for higher mortgage default. The banks are most
sensitive to charges about their loan policies towards small businesses.
There are two accusations against them: that their minimum lending rates
keep loan interest payments artificially high; and that they are covertly
keeping back part of base rate cuts.
Barclays and National Westminster set minimum lending rates to ensure
profitability at low levels of base rates. Until Wednesday, National
Westminster's minimum rate on small business loans was 11 per cent. The
average such loan cost 11.5 per cent, or 3.5 percentage points above the
base rate.
There was a danger that a base rate cut to 7 per cent - which happened on
Thursday - would have resulted in the bank responding with only 1/2
percentage point cut in the small business rate. Having been bitten several
times before, both banks cut their minimum rate to prevent this.
The second issue for banks is the overall movement in what they charge small
businesses for loans. Margins vary according to each individual risk - for
example, Lloyds does not follow base rates precisely, but adjusts what it
calls 'managed business rates'. It has three bands - equivalent to spreads
of 3, 4 and 5 percentage points above the base rate - which it adjusts
roughly as base rates change. Mr Phil Nunnerley, assistant general manager
for retail banking, argues that the bank has 'fully mirrored' cuts in base
rates since last year.
Midland also says its small business loans have fallen in line with base
rates. It says the average gap has been 3.5 per cent for the past two years.
The recession has led to more customers being classified as high-risk, but
this has been balanced by more risky loans being written off.
However, both Barclays and National Westminster admit that their spreads on
business loans have risen - from around 3.1 points 18 months ago to some 3.5
per cent today. Ms Jane Bradford, National Westminster's head of small
business services, says that reflects higher risk.
Building society mortgage rates have gradually diverged from base rates in
the past two years. The difference between them is historically high, after
being squeezed in the late 1980s when societies competed to offer mortgages.
Societies are trying to regain profitability by widening the margin.
The mortgage rate in 1980 was 1.4 percentage points below the base rate on
average, according to the securities firm UBS Philip &amp; Drew. For most of the
1980s, mortgage rates were above base rates while societies rebuilt
profitability.
However, in 1989, mortgage rates were again lower. There has since been a
return to mortgage rates exceeding base rates, the difference last year
being 1.2 points on average.
The societies stand accused of two sins: widening their margins, and
delaying cuts in rates for borrowers so that new ones are at an advantage.
Mr John Wriglesworth, an analyst at UBS Phillips and Drew, argues that
criticisms are unfair because the industry needs to raise profit-ability.
Mr Wriglesworth says lower rates hurt societies' balance sheets because they
are earning less interest on their own reserves. They also need to raise
their margins because they are hurt by rising repossessions. Bad debts have
risen from Pounds 20m five years ago to an estimated Pounds 2bn this year.
He says that if societies had not delayed cuts in mortgage rates for
existing borrowers, they would have been unable to cut mortgage rates as
much as they have done.
Mr Terry Payton, head of group finance at Alliance and Leicester, argues
that building societies both need to take account of the increased risk in
the housing market and to try to attract more savings. 'We are trying to
balance both sides of the equation, and help the saver as well,' he says.
The upshot is that banks and building societies are risking the public
opprobrium of widening margins because commercial pressures are proving too
heavy to resist.
Charges attacked, Page 10
Letters, Page 19
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
