<HEADLINE>
FT  17 NOV 92 / Keeping a lid on Cumbria's nuclear dustbin: David Lascelles
on the debate over authorisation of the reprocessing facility
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID LASCELLES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE FUTURE of British Nuclear Fuel's new reprocessing plant at Sellafield
should, technically, be decided by the authorisation process which was set
in motion yesterday by the Pollution Inspectorate.
The real question, however, is whether political feelings over this
controversial project now run so high that ministers from several government
departments will feel obliged to intervene.
The inspectorate's proposals are unlikely to allay widespread public concern
about the health risks posed by the plant, and its role as what
environmental lobbyists describe as a 'nuclear dustbin'. Mr Michael Howard,
the environment secretary, has powers to call for a public hearing, and he
will be watching the coming debate closely.
Not that the pollution inspectorate intends to give Sellafield's Thorp plant
an easy ride. The 2in-thick draft authorisation issued for public discussion
yesterday sets much tougher limits for radioactive emissions than British
Nuclear Fuels asked for. The inspectorate will continue to tighten these up
to reduce Sellafield's radiological impact still further, and officials
stress that their policy is to 'screw down' standards.
But the inspectorate's brief is narrow. Its main task is to ensure that
British Nuclear Fuels, like other polluting industries, uses the best
available technology to clean up its act within the bounds of reasonable
cost. Although this addresses the environmental issue, the 'green' lobby has
already taken the argument over Sellafield far beyond that issue and is now
questioning its very existence.
The coming debate will raise many issues. One is whether Thorp is even
commercially viable, as British Nuclear Fuels claims it is. Built at a cost
of Pounds 1.85bn over eight years, it is designed to handle spent fuel from
the new generation of pressurised-water reactors. One of only two in the
world - the other is near Cherbourg in France - its order books are full for
the first 10 years, and 40 per cent full for the following decade. British
Nuclear Fuels claims that this Pounds 9bn of business will generate Pounds
500m of profits in the first 10 years.
But critics claim that its assumptions are too optimistic. What is clear is
that the high costs of reprocessing are already driving potential customers
away, and the cheaper alternative of storing spent fuel is becoming more
attractive. Although existing customers will have to compensate British
Nuclear Fuels if they break their contracts, there is a danger that the
plant could become redundant.
This is a matter for the Department of Trade and Industry, which is keen to
see British Nuclear Fuels succeed because of its advanced technology and
contribution to exports. But it will also be a matter for the Treasury,
which will have to balance Sellafield's earning power against its wider
financial and other costs.
Another issue has already been sparked by the row over the recent shipment
of a tonne of processed plutonium by the French plant back to Japan. British
Nuclear Fuel's contracts oblige its customers to take back their processed
waste, but the possibility of some kind of ban on international shipments of
dangerous materials could lead to it having to nurse other countries'
nuclear rubbish. As it is, the company will be left with the residue and its
own irradiated equipment.
There is also a conflict between the UK's desire to restrict the spread of
nuclear weapons and its encouragement of an industry that ships around the
world large amounts of material that could have military applications.
Although it may be a year or two before Sellafield has to start shipping
processed plutonium of its own, there are clearly issues here for the
Foreign Office. A factor might be the change of administration in the US
where Mr Bill Clinton, the president-elect, is expected to take a much
tougher line against nuclear waste.
Although this period of consultation was always foreseen and does not, as
many of the company's critics claim, mark a last-minute effort by ministers
to halt Thorp, it comes at a sensitive time. What should have been a routine
final step in Thorp's authorisation threatens to become an important
investigation into its future.
Mr Howard will have to weigh a complex set of considerations as he decides
whether to step in. The picture could be further complicated by judicial
challenges to the inspectorate and the Department of the Environment by
activist lobby groups. One observer remarked: 'It's one of those cases where
you're damned if you do and damned if you don't'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 7
</PAGE>
