<HEADLINE>
FT  17 NOV 92 / Sellafield plant faces tough safety standards
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID LASCELLES, Resources Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
POLLUTION authorities proposed tough new standards yesterday for British
Nuclear Fuels' new waste processing plant at Sellafield in Cumbria.
But while they claimed these would result in significantly lower discharges
of harmful materials, the proposals did not include a requirement to install
control equipment on a controversial radioactive gas.
The new standards could leave room for an increase in discharges from
current levels. The Pollution Inspectorate's proposals are contained in a
draft authorisation for the Sellafield site, including the Thermal Oxide
Reprocessing Plant (Thorp), a new Pounds 1.85bn facility designed to process
fuel from pressurised-water reactors.
There will be an eight-week consultation period, after which a final
authorisation will be drawn up.
Dr David Slater, the inspectorate's director, said yesterday: 'I emphasise
that no decisions will be taken until we have considered all the
representations made to us.' Mr Michael Howard, the environment secretary,
has the power to call for a full hearing if he wishes.
The proposed emission levels are tougher than BNF requested. But the company
welcomed them last night.
Mr John Guinness, the chairman, said he was convinced that the inspectorate
would be 'scrupulous and fair' and would not be swayed by 'the tactics of
the anti-nuclear lobby which has been orchestrating a letters campaign in
order to distort the right and proper process of public consultation'.
Dr Patrick Green of the environmental pressure group Friends of the Earth
said: 'Far from preventing further contamination of the coast and
atmosphere, the Pollution Inspectorate is planning to let BNF increase
massively its discharges to the environment.'
The proposed maximum limit on gases would reduce the annual radiation dose
to the most exposed members of the public from 451 microsieverts to 214ms.
However, Sellafield's emissions are currently only 170ms.
The maximum for liquid wastes at present allows a dose of 219ms, against
actual emissions amounting to 135ms to 153ms. The new limit would be 165ms,
again leaving room for an increase.
The inspectorate stressed yesterday, however, that British Nuclear Fuels
would have to stay within 75 per cent of the limit.
The inspectorate is not requiring British Nuclear Fuels to install equipment
to remove krypton-85, a radioactive gas that will be discharged into the
atmosphere by Thorp.
The inspectorate said there was no proven and safe means. But BNF would have
to install the equipment as soon as 'reasonably practicable'.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 7
</PAGE>
