FT  17 NOV 92 / Canada forced to protect currency
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD SIMON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TORONTO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A BURST of gloomy reports on Canada's economic prospects has sent the
Canadian dollar reeling, forced interest rates higher and raised fresh
concern about the sputtering business recovery.
The Canadian dollar sank by almost half a US cent yesterday, falling below
79 US cents for the first time in almost five years and closing at 78.60.
The Bank of Canada responded by pushing up short-term interest rates.
Commercial banks followed suit, lifting prime rates by three-quarters of a
percentage point to 8.25 per cent.
Economists are concerned that the jump in interest rates will rub out signs
of an end to the unexpectedly long and deep recession. With inflation
running at an annual rate of little more than 1 per cent, real long-term
interest rates are now at an unusually high level of about 8 per cent.
Mr Warren Jestin, chief economist at Bank of Nova Scotia, said yesterday
that Canada was teetering 'on the lip of deflation'. Financial markets'
nervousness is ascribed to worries about deteriorating federal and
provincial finances.
