<HEADLINE>
FT  17 NOV 92 / Credit surge poses threat of inflation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BEIJING
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
CHINA'S rush to develop a market economy is fuelling a surge in credit to
fund inefficient capital investment, the People's Daily has said, Reuter
reports from Beijing.
'The call for faster economic development does not mean that everyone must
jump to the fore,' the Communist Party's official newspaper said.
'We must not take the old road of neglecting efficiency, stressing and
competing only for production value, blindly launching new projects and
expanding production.
While proud that their economic policies are working, China's communist
leaders fear that mismanagement may bring a repeat of the economic
turbulence of the late 1980s, when spiralling inflation helped to spur the
pro-democracy protests in the spring of 1989.
China's economy grew by 10.6 per cent in the first three quarters of 1992,
down from rates of up to 12 per cent earlier this year. Inflation remains at
about 5 per cent, according to official statistics, but urban areas are
posting rates closer to 10 per cent, which diplomats say are still
underestimated.
</TEXT>
