<HEADLINE>
FT  17 NOV 92 / China faces inflation threat
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BEIJING
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
CHINA'S headlong rush to develop a market economy is fuelling a surge in
credit to fund inefficient capital investment, the People's Daily has said,
Reuter reports from Beijing.
'The call for faster economic development does not mean that everyone must
jump to the fore,' the Communist Party's official newspaper said.
'We must not take the old road of neglecting efficiency, stressing and
competing only for production value, blindly launching new projects and
expanding production.
'If we do not look at the reality, and do not recognise that speed without
efficiency will not last long, then it will create economic chaos.'
While proud that their economic policies are working, China's communist
leaders fear that that mismanagement may bring a repeat of the economic
turbulence of the late 1980s, when spiralling inflation helped to spur the
pro-democracy protests in the spring of 1989.
Inflation remains at about 5 per cent, according to official statistics, but
urban areas are posting rates closer to 10 per cent, which diplomats say are
still underestimated.
Warnings of overproduction and the inflationary threat have become more
frequent following last month's Communist Party congress, which thrilled
China's budding entrepreneurs by setting its seal of approval on
market-style reforms.
Grandiose development schemes and plans for faster production are being
unveiled across the country. Industrial projects valued at Dollars 185bn
(Pounds 122.5bn) are now under construction in the state sector, a figure
equal to about one half of China's annual GNP, according to official
statistics.
The People's Daily said the main problem facing China's economic planners
was inefficiency, especially in the state sector where companies are revving
up production lines to churn out piles of shoddy, unwanted goods.
China's gross industrial output during the first nine months was slightly
over 2,000bn yuan (Pounds 245bn) an increase of 19.3 per cent over the same
period in 1991.
By the end of August the total value of finished industrial goods unbought
in warehouses hit a Dollars 25bn, an increase of Dollars 4.4bn from the
start of the year.
</TEXT>
