<HEADLINE>
FT  17 NOV 92 / Kingfisher moves into UK office stationery
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MAGGIE URRY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
KINGFISHER, the retail conglomerate, is moving into the UK office stationery
and equipment market though a joint venture with Staples Inc, the fast
growing US chain. The partnership plans to open four stores in the UK next
year, with each side investing up Dollars 6m (Pounds 4m) initially to test
the market.
The stores will be based on the format Staples has developed in the US,
under the name Staples The Office Superstores.
In the US the stores are mainly sited out of town and sell everything from
drawing pins to personal computers, aiming to combine a wide range with
'everyday low prices'.
The stores also produce a catalogue and deliver orders made over the
telephone, which represent under 10 per cent of its sales. Staples says that
businesses with fewer than 100 employees find it 'cumbersome to shop our
retail stores'.
The UK office supply market is worth about Pounds 12bn but the venture is
aiming at a sector worth Pounds 1.5bn a year. The market is fragmented and
many of the wholesalers supplying the market make good margins.
WH Smith, the high street stationers and newspaper and magazine wholesaler,
has already identified the market as providing a growth opportunity. Smith
has acquired a number of stationery wholesalers and recently launched a new
brand in the market called Niceday.
Kingfisher, which runs the Woolworth, Comet, Superdrug and B&amp;Q chains, said
it had been approached by Staples, which is keen to expand outside the US.
Kingfisher decided it was better to take a successful format rather than
attempt to develop its own. Staples has joint ventures in Canada and
Germany.
Mr Thomas Stemberg, Staples chairman and chief executive, said that
Kingfisher's knowledge of the UK retail market combined with Staples'
expertise in office superstores 'create a sound opportunity for joint growth
and expansion'.
Staples opened its first superstore in 1986 and now has 168, based in the
north-east, southern California and central Florida. Sales have risen from
Dollars 39.7m in 1988 to Dollars 547.1m in the year to February 1. Net
losses of Dollars 7.7m incurred in 1988 have turned to income of Dollars
7.9m before extraordinary credits, in 1991-92.
Lex, Page 20
</TEXT>
