<HEADLINE>
FT  17 NOV 92 / Midlands light rail authority invites tenders
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL CHEESERIGHT, Midlands Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FOUR private-sector consortia have been invited to tender for a Pounds 100m
contract to design, build and operate a light-rail transport system in
Birmingham and the Black Country.
The tender has been called by Centro, the operating arm of the West Midlands
Passenger Transport Authority. It is part of a renewed effort to persuade
the government to provide funding for a project which, it is argued, fits
into its policy of encouraging private and public sector partnerships in
infrastructure development.
Centro suspended its tendering process for the light-rail system last June,
when the government said there would be no funding available to start
construction in April 1993. Now, Centro officials believe, a new opportunity
to start the project, called Midland Metro, has come with last week's Autumn
Statement.
Mr Norman Lamont, the chancellor, said then that the government would
'actively encourage joint ventures with the private sector where these
involve a sensible transfer of risk to the private sector'.
Existing plans for Midland Metro provide for only 10 per cent of the Pounds
100m cost to come from the private sector. The remainder would be provided
by central government with Pounds 40m, local authority borrowing with Pounds
40m and the European Community with Pounds 10m.
Midland Metro's first line would run from central Birmingham through West
Bromwich and Bilston to Wolverhampton. The government has provided Pounds
4.5m to help finance advance works. It is the only planned line in the UK
which has won parliamentary and Department of Transport approval.
Centro said yesterday that a government grant of Pounds 10m would enable
construction to start next year. Tendering would be completed by April. But
this assumes an extra government funding allocation to light-rail systems.
The four tendering consortia are:
Civil engineering group Balfour Beatty and German electrical group Siemens.
Centram, made up of construction company Taylor Woodrow and Ansaldo
Transporti, subsidiary of the Italian Finmeccanica group.
Construction group John Mowlem and GEC Alsthom Transportation.
Eurotransit, made up of Norwest Holst, subsidiary of French construction
group Societe Generale d'Entreprises, contractor Tilbury Douglas and AEG
Westinghouse Transport Systems.
</TEXT>
