<HEADLINE>
FT  16 NOV 92 / International Company News: Baxter International forms
Moscow venture
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   DEERFIELD
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
BAXTER International, the US hospital equipment group, is to form a 75 per
cent-owned manufacturing venture in Russia to produce surgical instruments
at a Moscow plant that once produced defence missile guidance systems. The
move represents Baxter's first entry into manufacturing in Russia, Reuter
reports from Deerfield.
NIIAP, a Russian manufacturing enterprise, will own the remaining 25 per
cent of the venture, which was established with the assistance of the
Russian Ministry of Health and the Department of General Machine Building.
Baxter said production at the plant will begin in June 1993 with full
production expected in 1994. Its statement provided no volume expectations,
but did say 200 would be employed.
Baxter said: 'If we are successful in this venture we may explore bringing
other technologies - including blood products, intravenous solutions and
renal therapy - to Russia.'
The venture would manufacture hand-held surgical instruments such as
vascular clamps, scissors and needle holders with support from Baxter's V.
Mueller division, it added.
The company said Russian producers are able to supply only about 30 per cent
of current demand for such products.
