<HEADLINE>
FT  16 NOV 92 / Ministers accuse Labour of 'muck-raking' on Iraq arms
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH and RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SENIOR MINISTERS accused Labour of 'muck-raking' in its attempts to put Mr
John Major in the dock over the sale of defence related material to Iraq, as
the political storm about the Matrix Churchill prosecution entered its
second week.
The opposition warned that pressure on the government would increase rather
than diminish. Mr Robin Cook, the shadow trade secretary, said he would
produce today further 'damning evidence' linking the prime minister with the
affair.
Speaking on BBC radio, Mr Tony Newton, the leader of the Commons, said there
seemed to be a concerted effort by the opposition to tarnish Mr Major as in
the case of the collapse of the Bank of Credit and Commerce International.
He noted that Mr Major had been cleared in the Bingham report into the
collapse.
Similarly, in an interview on the Walden television programme, Mr John
MacGregor, the transport secretary, expressed confidence that the government
would be vindicated in the independent judicial inquiry announced last
Tuesday, and accused opposition parties of 'an attempt to muck-rake in the
hope that the initial allegations will stick in the public mind'.
In a move that underlines how seriously the government is taking the issue,
Mr Major issued on Saturday a vigorous defence of his role in the Matrix
Churchill affair, saying that Mr Cook should confine his comments 'to fact
and not innuendo'.
Mr Major said that while he was foreign secretary briefly in 1989 he had not
been told of the row between junior ministers about exports to Iraq, nor had
he been briefed to raise the matter with Mr Tariq Aziz, the Iraqi foreign
minister, whom he met in September 1989.
While Labour concentrates on Mr Major's role as foreign secretary, some of
the most recent revelations highlight the fact that the government was
clearing export licences for the last batch of Matrix Churchill machine
tools the very day before the Iraqi invasion of Kuwait in 1990.
Denying any government attempt at a 'cover up', ministers emphasised that
the inquiry into the affair, to be headed by Lord Justice Scott, would be
wide enough to enable the investigation of all the issues raised. The terms
of reference are expected to be announced this week.
Among Tory backbenchers, the main concern appears to be the way that Customs
and Excise were able to proceed independently with the Matrix Churchill
prosecutions despite the knowledge within government that the executives on
trial had been working for the security services, rather than the details of
the sale of machine tools to Iraq.
Mr Paddy Ashdown, the Liberal Democrat leader, yesterday called for an
emergency Commons debate on the arms-for-Iraq affair. MPs have, however,
lost an immediate opportunity to discuss the issue, because last week the
Liberal Democrats did not choose the affair for debate today - one of the
rare occasions when opposition parties decide what the Commons discusses.
