FT  16 NOV 92 / Observer: Stepping over
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Meanwhile, the faces at the top of London's stockbroking firms continue to
change with unseemly speed. UBS Phillips &amp; Drew has lost two heads of
research in little more than a month, and now Mike Geering, James Capel's
research chief, is moving into fund management and Nick Whitney, a veteran
of several houses, is resurfacing as managing director of Hoare Govett,
leaving chairman Peter Meinertzhagen free to concentrate on the group's core
corporate finance business.
Of the latest moves, Whitney's could prove to be the more hazardous.
Geering, who is joining Mercury Asset Management, is treading a well worn
path. Keith Percy and Ken Inglis, two of
P &amp; D's best research bosses, have both made successful career moves into
fund management, as has Tim Ferguson, a former County NatWest research
chieftain.
Fund management may not be as well paid as running and researching equities,
but it has its advantages. Not only are there fewer conflicts of interest,
but there are fewer big egos to manage and the profits are more reliable.
