<HEADLINE>
FT  16 NOV 92 / Protests over Companies House changes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
USERS OF Companies House, which stores information on more than 1m UK
limited companies, have protested about new consultation procedures, saying
it will be harder to put their views across.
The Users Group, which has been a forum for customers of Companies' House
for 19 years, is being replaced by several specialist committees.
The users, including registration agents, credit agencies, chambers of
commerce, solicitors and accountants, complain that the procedures have been
introduced abruptly and that there will be restrictions on free discussion.
They argue that as Companies House has a monopoly on company registrations
consultation with its customers is essential.
Companies House plans at least four specialist user committees covering
large users, such as business information and credit-rating agencies; banks;
solicitors and accountants; and smaller credit agencies and chambers of
commerce.
Companies House says more focused discussions on specialist issues will be
feasible than was possible with the Users' Group, which typically attracted
between 20 and 30 people to its quarterly meetings.
A Companies House official said: 'The Users' Group was getting too big and
too general. The smaller groups will allow us to draw our specialist staff
into the discussions.'
Members of the group believe, however, that Mr David Durham, the chief
executive and Companies House staff, resented criticisms and comments made
at the Users' Group meetings.
Mr Terry Robinson, vice-president of the Institute of Credit Management,
said: 'At times they acted as a ginger group and I wonder whether the reason
for disbanding the Users' Group was that they they felt they could do
without the criticism.'
Mr George Corderoy, chairman of the Law Services Association, a grouping of
registration agents, said: 'The opportunity for a general debate will be
lost in the specialist committees.'
Members also believe that Companies House, an executive agency since 1988
and likely to be privatised in the next year or so, felt uneasy at taking
criticism from organisations which were increasingly becoming competitors.
Competition has come particularly from the search agents, which compile
company profiles from information supplied by Companies House.
</TEXT>
