<HEADLINE>
FT  16 NOV 92 / Forum on training formed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART and BOB LITTLE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MORE THAN 100 national employers have formed a pressure group to represent
their views to the government on the structure and funding of training.
The National Employers' and Training Providers' Forum was established in
Northampton last week by representatives from several big employers
including British Gas, Eagle Star Insurance, IBM UK, Marks and Spencer, B&amp;Q
and Royal Mail.
Mr Roger Shaw of the British Printing Industries Federation, the forum's
chairman, said: 'Unity among major employers and providers of youth/adult
training is essential.'
Mr Trevor Thornett, British Gas's senior training adviser, said: 'Basically
we support the government's initiatives - including the proposed National
Managing Agency - but we feel it is important to make our views on training
provision and funding known.'
G10, the group which represents the views of Tec leaders to government, has
said it is 'delighted' that Tec budgets emerged largely unscathed from last
week's Autumn Statement. Mr Edward Roberts, the chairman, praised Mrs
Gillian Shephard, employment secretary for the way she 'fought the Tecs'
corner at a very difficult time'.
</TEXT>
