<HEADLINE>
FT  16 NOV 92 / Tecs move 'undercuts chambers'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TRAINING AND Enterprise Councils (Tecs) are developing membership schemes
that compete directly with chambers of commerce and undercut the chambers'
subscriptions.
This is one of the main findings of a survey of the Tecs in England and
Wales and Local Enterprise Companies (Lecs), their Scottish equivalents,
published today by the London School of Economics.
The study says that Tecs, which were envisaged as working with local
organisations rather than having memberships of their own, are competing
with chambers in small-business advice to members.
It shows Tecs charge an average annual subscription of Pounds 32, compared
with the chambers' average of Pounds 131.
Mr Robert Bennett, author of the report, said the government encouraged the
Tecs to set up membership schemes by means of performance bonuses but the
purpose of this policy was not entirely clear.
The survey noted that Tecs clearly planned to set themselves up in
competition with the chambers.
The G10 group of chief executives of 10 large Tecs claimed Tecs had a
membership of 100,000 in a recent submission to the department of trade and
industry.
Tecs and Lecs: Survey of New Developments. LSE, Houghton Street, London WC2A
2AE.
</TEXT>
