<HEADLINE>
FT  16 NOV 92 / Bucking the Trend: A magnificent deal with the greatest of
ease - In spite of the widespread gloom in industry, a surprising number of
companies are thriving against the odds. This is the first in a series on
companies - often small and relatively unknown - which are scoring successes
in the recession
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL BETTS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A TINY North Yorkshire company is tooling up to supply aircraft to the US
Air Force against a background of the worst recession to hit the UK's
aerospace and defence industries since the Second World War.
Slingsby has just landed the most important contract in its 60-year history
and its production of small propeller-driven military training aircraft will
double.
The company is based in a cluster of sheds which looks more like a farm than
a factory, just outside Kirkbymoorside on the edge of the north Yorkshire
moors.
The US Air Force has chosen Slingsby's T-67 Firefly aircraft as its new
basic trainer for pilots. Slingsby won an order from the US Air Force for up
to 113 Firefly trainers worth about Dollars 50m (Pounds 33.1m) after a
fierce international competition.
To win the order the small Yorkshire company, with annual sales of about
Pounds 7m, teamed up with Northrop, one of the giants of the US defence
industry.
Mr John Dignan, Slingsby's marketing director, said: 'This is really a case
of the mouse that roared.' The company will soon start shipping the aircraft
kits to the US for assembly by Northrop at Hondo in Texas.
The order came at an excellent time for Slingsby. Mr Michael Jones, a group
executive of ML Holdings, the engineering group which acquired Slingsby
eight years ago, said: 'Like everybody else we have had to cut back this
year because of the recession and the lack of work in the aerospace
business.'
However, Mr Jones said that after reducing its workforce from 202 to 140
people this year, the company's payroll was now expected to rise to 230.
Mr David Holt, Slingsby's managing director, said: 'Our production will more
than double from about four aircraft a month to nine a month. We've had to
gut our factory space and refurbish it to prepare for this big jump in
production.'
The company was founded in the early 1930s by a carpenter from Scarborough,
Mr Fred Slingsby, and originally made gliders and sailplanes.
Slingsby is still known locally as 'the glider company', but has evolved in
the last 20 years under a series of owners, including Vickers and British
Underwater Engineering.
It is now a high-technology designer and manufacturer of composite products
and components for the aerospace and marine industries.
The company supplies parts to some of the world's biggest aerospace
manufacturers including Boeing, Airbus and British Aerospace. It also
designs and makes parts for airships and underwater equipment and robots for
the offshore oil industry.
Mr Dignan said: 'It has taken us 10 years to establish the aircraft in the
market and we expect we will now win many new orders on the back of the US
Air Force deal.'
The first 10 Slingsby two-seater aircraft were built of wood on a licence
from Fournier, a French light-aircraft manufacturer.
In 1983 the North Yorkshire company applied its expertise in composite
materials to develop an all-composite version of the aircraft.
Since then, excluding the new US contract, the company has sold 104 trainers
to 10 countries, including Switzerland, Turkey, Canada, Hong Kong, the
Netherlands and Norway.
It claims the Firefly is now in a good position to be chosen as the new
primary trainer for the Royal Air Force, which is due to decide on an order
for 20 aircraft next month.
One of the aircraft's selling points is that it can perform, on a small
scale, many of the tasks of a sophisticated fighter aircraft.
Mr Norrie Grove, Slingsby's chief test pilot and a Spitfire veteran, said:
'This aeroplane is designed to train a pilot at the most important stage of
his early career, when he is learning the basic skills.'
It is expected that in the next five years 25 countries will replace their
primary military trainers, involving about 520 aircraft worth Dollars 300m
to Dollars 500m over the next 10 years.
Mr Dignan said: 'There are six manufacturers competing for this business and
there is not room for everyone.'
Slingsby has some advantages. Its labour costs are relatively low and the
company is one of the rare manufacturers in an area of small market towns,
enabling it to keep a stable local base of skilled labour. In its own tiny
way, Slingsby has become the Boeing of Kirkbymoorside.
</TEXT>
