<HEADLINE>
FT  16 NOV 92 / Editor of Daily Mirror is sacked
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MR RICHARD STOTT was yesterday sacked as editor of the Daily Mirror
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
the second newspaper editor to be removed from Mirror Group Newspapers in
under a week.
MGN said his successor, Mr David Banks, was joining the company 'without any
of the Maxwell experience that still infects the operation'. MGN also said
the Daily Mirror would stick to its line of trying to help the election of a
Labour government. But there would be a 'more modern approach' to political
coverage. One executive said there would be less 'ranting propaganda'.
The paper would also seek to recapture its crusading spirit 'on issues of
real concern to readers, like mortgages and other consumer issues'.
Mr Stott, who edited both the Daily Mirror and the People twice and had
worked for MGN for 24 years, left as Mr Banks flew in from Australia. Mr
Banks, 44, was editor of the Telegraph Mirror in Sydney. He has also been
deputy editor of The Australian and night editor of The Sun in London.
Mr Banks said: 'Today we finally bury Maxwell at the Daily Mirror. This is a
new beginning.'
Last week Mr Bill Hagerty was removed as editor of The People. MGN said
yesterday his successor would be Ms Bridget Rowe, editor of the Sunday
Mirror. Ms Rowe will be succeeded by her deputy, Mr Colin Myler - a former
news editor at Today under the editorship of Mr David Montgomery.
The changes follow last month's appointment of Mr Montgomery, former editor
of the News of the World as well as Today, as MGN chief executive.
Daily Mirror journalists last night described the events as 'the beginning
of the end'. A statement said: 'Three weeks after he promised editorial
independence and assured us that editorial jobs were safe, David Montgomery
has sacked two out of three editors.'
Observer, Page 13
</TEXT>
