<HEADLINE>
FT  16 NOV 92 / Coal county fears loss of its strongest prop: Paul
Cheeseright explains why Nottinghamshire has lost its former resilience
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL CHEESERIGHT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE LATEST round of pit closures will hit Nottinghamshire harder than those
of the 1980s. Then, the county's economy was more robust and there were
plenty of older miners who could retire early. Now the average age of
Nottinghamshire miners is only 33.
Fears that colliery closures could lead to a 15 per cent shrinkage of the
county's gross domestic product were aired last week in an inquiry into the
future of the coalfields conducted for Nottinghamshire County Council by Mr
Anthony Scrivener QC.
Nottinghamshire County Council complains that 'there has been no special
government assistance for the area, yet job losses equal those of three
Ravenscraigs and four Consetts' - a reference to steel-industry closures
which attracted government help.
The decline of the coal industry in the county has coincided with a
reduction of employment in engineering and traditional industries such as
textiles.
In early 1981 Nottinghamshire was the most prosperous county in the East
Midlands, measured by gross domestic product per capita. Its GDP was 103 per
cent of the UK average. By the end of the decade this had fallen to 97.5 per
cent. In the region the county had been overtaken by Leicestershire and
Northamptonshire.
In the 1980s there was a marked increase of employment in the services
sector, albeit off a low base, but the most striking characteristic in the
jobs pattern of the county economy was the diminished role of coal mining.
Since 1980 17 collieries have been closed with the loss of 26,000 jobs.
It is not clear to what extent those who lost their jobs have been absorbed
into the economy. There are no statistics to show how many miners retired,
how many found other jobs or how many remained unemployed. It is clear,
however, that the effect on the economy was severe.
The 1989 census of employment showed that 2 per cent of the UK workforce was
engaged in the water and energy industries, but in the Nottinghamshire coal
area the proportion was 12 per cent and, in rural areas, where most of the
coal mines were, the proportion was 34.1 per cent.
Direct coal-mine employment has fallen since 1980 from more than 38,000 to
fewer than 14,000. Under British Coal's initial proposals a further seven
pits, employing 5,680 directly, would have been shut.
This number has been reduced to two in the immediate future as a result of
the announcement last week by Mr Michael Heseltine, the trade and industry
secretary. They are Cotgrave, south of Nottingham, and Silverhill, in the
Alfreton-Ashfield area, employing 1,340 miners. The remaining five await the
outcome of Mr Heseltine's review.
The future of the county coal industry is thus uncertain. The stakes are
higher than simple colliery closures, however. British Coal in
Nottinghamshire has been paying out more than Pounds 260m a year in wages
and salaries. The county coal mines have been buying in goods and services
worth more than Pounds 210m a year. The coal mines are among the biggest
customers of East Midlands Electricity, spending more than Pounds 28m a
year.
Nottinghamshire County Council calculates that, for every two jobs which
disappear from the mines, another goes outside. It fears for the future of
the local coal-fired power stations. It is worried that the removal of
spending power from the economy will result in the atrophy of economic
activity, hitting the leisure and recreation industries first.
The pains of more coal-mine closures will vary in their severity. Cotgrave
and Calverton - the latter is on the review list - are on the fringe of the
diversified Nottingham city economy. Here the opportunities for employment
are likely to be higher than in the Alfreton-Ashfield and Mansfield areas,
where the other collieries - Bilsthorpe, Clipstone, Rufford, Bevercotes and
Silverhill - are situated.
Male unemployment rates in Mansfield are 20 per cent and in
Alfreton-Ashfield 14.5 per cent, explaining the government's decision to
grant Mansfield assisted-area status.
Unemployment rates are running consistently above the national average and
it seems that the expansion of the services sector has not been enough to
cope with the pains of a restructuring economy.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
