<HEADLINE>
FT  16 NOV 92 / Union challenge to 24-hour banking
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Bifu banking, insurance and finance union is considering industrial
action against TSB, Britain's sixth biggest bank, which is planning an
around-the-clock telephone banking service.
The experimental telephone service, staffed 24 hours a day, 365 days a year,
will offer full banking and insurance services.
Bifu, which represents about 90 per cent of TSB's 25,000 employees in
Britain, believes the changes, which TSB is to evaluate with a view to their
introduction nationally, are bound to mean job cuts and a poorer career
structure, with fewer branch-manager posts and a reduction in skilled jobs.
Mr David Carter, Bifu north-east England organiser, said: 'It will set the
precedent nationally. We aren't going to stand in the way of progress but
it's a question of how they do it.'
The Teleservice project is part of an Pounds 8.5m package of measures,
including weekday evening and all-day Saturday opening, which are being
introduced as a prototype into Tyneside, a TSB strong-hold.
TSB said the experiment, which included increased automation of branches and
the closure of a small number of its 22 Tyneside outlets, was aimed at
enhancing its services. It would not mean job losses.
Tyneside has been chosen for the experiment because it has a strong TSB
customer base and a large network of branches.
The bank is also investing Pounds 1.5m in its sole Watford branch to see if
upgraded services there can win more customers.
The Gateshead-based service, initially for use only by Tyneside and Watford
TSB customers, has started operating during the day, but will start
around-the-clock operation in February.
