FT  16 NOV 92 / Call for action on laundering
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DANIEL GREEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
INTERNATIONAL co-ordination is needed to counter the use of electronic
payment networks by criminals laundering the proceeds of drug trafficking
and robberies, the Bank of England warns this week.
The Bank says in an article to appear in its Quarterly Bulletin on Thursday:
'The increasing efficiency and integration of the world's financial system
creates an environment that organised criminals are only too ready to
exploit.'
The Bank is one of the seven founding members of the international Financial
Action Task Force, which is the main forum focused on combating money
laundering.
The task force has been particularly concerned that many electronic payment
instructions 'fail to include the names and addresses of both senders and
beneficiaries'.
As a result the Society for Worldwide Interbank Financial Telecommunications
has told all its clients to include these details.
Few money launderers are caught. In the UK only two employees of financial
institutions have been prosecuted for money laundering under Section 24 of
the Drug Trafficking Offences Act, although about 12,000 suspicious cash
movements are expected to be reported this year.
