FT  16 NOV 92 / South-east housing cost 'hits the young'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN, Public Policy Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE COST of housing in the south-east of England is forcing young people to
remain living with their parents and to put off starting a family, according
to a report published today by the Joseph Rowntree Foundation, the social
research organisation.
In a survey of people aged 18 to 35 in the south-east, one in seven said
that they had stayed with their parents for longer than they wished because
of concerns about the cost of a home. One in nine had delayed parenthood and
a similar number had delayed setting up home with their partner.
Of those with a mortgage, 60 per cent were paying more than Pounds 400 a
month. Those living with parents tended to pay only nominal rent.
The survey shows that only a minority of young people will get help from
their parents with housing costs. Less than a fifth of those who had left
home received any help.
The median amount was Pounds 1,000.
The effects of housing costs on young people's lifestyles, Joseph Rowntree
Foundation, 40 Water End, York YO3 6LP. Free.
