FT  16 NOV 92 / MPs may back energy body
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BACKBENCH MPs examining Britain's energy sector are seriously considering
the idea of setting up an energy agency to help oversee strategic
decision-making.
Under one possible model Offer and Ofgas, the electricity and gas industry
regulators, could be merged and given enhanced powers in formulating energy
policy.
This agency would not seek to usurp ultimate authority from government
ministers but would advise them on subjects such as the appropriate energy
mix for the country's interests and pollution-related matters. Any such move
 -aimed at correcting widely perceived shortcomings in the present regime -
would probably require legislation.
The all-party trade and industry select committee started its inquiries last
month in the wake of the announcement of controversial plans to close 31
coal pits and make 30,000 miners redundant. It is due to continue taking
evidence for a further month.
Chaired by Mr Richard Caborn, Labour MP for Sheffield Central, the committee
is expected to publish its recommendations soon after MPs return from the
Christmas recess in January.
Among a series of presentations arguing for a more interventionist approach
to energy strategy, the views of Mr Dieter Helm, the Oxford economist, are
thought to have been warmly received by MPs across the political spectrum.
Mr Helm argued in evidence to the committee for an energy agency 'quite
closely mirrored on the government's proposals for an environmental agency'.
He added: 'This agency may well have the duties to produce capacity
forecasts . . . and it may well have licensing powers.' Offer and Ofgas, he
said, did not have 'the wider interests or the relevant powers to conduct
energy policy'.
