FT  16 NOV 92 / Pension curbs opposed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
EMPLOYERS are strongly opposed to the prospect of pensions legislation
limiting their ability to use surpluses for their own purposes, accountancy
firm KPMG Peat Marwick found in a survey.
The government has commissioned an independent review of pension law under
Professor Roy Goode, whose committee has until next May to make
recommendations.
The 16 companies surveyed, all clients of KPMG, said employee contributions
to a pension scheme were fixed and intended to purchase a fixed level of
benefit in future.
They said surpluses arose when employers discovered that they had allocated
more than was needed to the fund, given the level of investment returns.
Employers should therefore have no restrictions on their ability to extract
surpluses, although they might choose to share some of a surplus with scheme
members.
The Future of Pensions; Proposals by a Group of Major UK Employers, KPMG
Peat Marwick Actuarial Services, 1 Puddle Dock Blackfriars, London EC4V 3PD.
