<HEADLINE>
FT  16 NOV 92 / Burgundy prices come down
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EDMUND PENNING-ROWSELL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BEAUNE
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Although Burgundy probably enjoyed the best vintage in France this year, the
depressed state of the market at yesterday's Hospices de Beaune auction of
its new wine led to a sharp drop in prices for the third year running,
writes Edmund Penning-Rowsell in Beaune.
Average price on the 567 casks of red wine fell by 21.8 per cent to
FFr17,242 (Pounds 2,113), and the 96 casks of white were lower by 25 per
cent to FFr21,625 (Pounds 2,650). Prices would have been lower but for the
constant intervention of the firm of Patriarche of Beaune which bought 26 of
the 81 lots on offer. The only prominent foreign buyers were Japanese; the
firm of Katsuski Joyama of Tokyo paid FFr60,000 a cask for the first lot of
Pommard Raymond Cyrot.
</TEXT>
